# 🔬 Corrected Prediction-to-Prescription Pipeline
## Flaw-Resolved Architecture — Tox21 Multi-Endpoint Optimization

---

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This document corrects 6 critical design flaws in the naive "Prediction to Prescription" approach. Each correction is mapped to a concrete implementation. The result is a scientifically defensible, potentially publishable research contribution.

---

## The Final Research Question (Post-Correction)

> **"Does SHAP-guided, synthesizability-filtered bioisostere substitution produce consistent multi-endpoint toxicity reductions in Tox21-flagged compounds — and what scaffold classes does the pipeline systematically fail on?"**

The failure mode analysis is the contribution. A clean positive result is a demo. An honest failure map is research.

---

## Architecture Overview

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["Input: SMILES String"] --> B["Step 1: Predict All 12 Tox21 Endpoints\n+ SHAP per endpoint"]
    B --> C["Step 1b: Cross-validate SHAP\nagainst Brenk/PAINS structural alerts\n→ Flag low-confidence attributions"]
    C --> D["Step 2: Map Top SHAP Bit → Molecular Fragment\n(Only if alert overlap confirmed)"]
    D --> E["Step 3: Query Bioisostere Database\n→ Filter: SAScore < 4\n→ Flag: Tanimoto to DrugBank < 0.4"]
    E --> F["Step 4: Re-predict All 12 Endpoints\n+ Conformal Prediction Intervals\n+ OOD Flag (Tanimoto to training set)"]
    F --> G["Output: Pareto Front\n12-endpoint toxicity profiles\nUncertainty bands\nSynthesizability score\nOOD flag\nAlert confidence"]
```

---

## Flaw 1 — Single Score → Pareto Front Across 12 Endpoints

### The Error
Optimizing `NR-AR: 0.82 → 0.31` while ignoring the other 11 endpoints is not safer — it is **invisible risk shifting**. A bioisostere swap reducing androgen receptor activity may raise mitochondrial membrane potential disruption (`SR-MMP`) by the same margin.

### The Correction: Pareto Dominance Check

```python
import numpy as np

def pareto_dominates(A: np.ndarray, B: np.ndarray) -> bool:
    """
    Returns True if candidate A Pareto-dominates B.
    A dominates B if A is <= B on ALL 12 endpoints and 
    strictly < B on at least one.
    (Lower toxicity probability = better)
    """
    return np.all(A <= B) and np.any(A < B)

def evaluate_swap_pareto(original_scores: np.ndarray, 
                          modified_scores: np.ndarray,
                          target_names: list) -> dict:
    """
    Full 12-endpoint evaluation of a proposed bioisostere swap.
    
    Returns:
        status: 'DOMINATES' | 'DOMINATED' | 'TRADE-OFF' | 'NO_CHANGE'
        improved: list of endpoints that got better
        worsened: list of endpoints that got worse
        net_change: per-endpoint delta
    """
    delta = modified_scores - original_scores  # negative = improved
    
    improved = [target_names[i] for i in range(12) if delta[i] < -0.05]
    worsened = [target_names[i] for i in range(12) if delta[i] > +0.05]
    
    if pareto_dominates(modified_scores, original_scores):
        status = 'DOMINATES'    # Genuinely safer across the board
    elif pareto_dominates(original_scores, modified_scores):
        status = 'DOMINATED'    # Made it worse — reject
    elif len(improved) > 0 and len(worsened) > 0:
        status = 'TRADE-OFF'    # Mixed — show the user, let them decide
    else:
        status = 'NO_CHANGE'
    
    return {
        'status': status,
        'improved_endpoints': improved,
        'worsened_endpoints': worsened,
        'delta_per_endpoint': dict(zip(target_names, delta.tolist())),
        'net_burden_change': float(delta.sum())  # aggregate signal
    }
```

### Dashboard Output (What the User Sees)

```
Proposed Swap: -Cl → -F on position 4

NR-AR       ████░░░░░░  0.82 → 0.31  ✅ -0.51
NR-ER       ████░░░░░░  0.71 → 0.28  ✅ -0.43  
SR-MMP      ██░░░░░░░░  0.31 → 0.67  ⚠️ +0.36  ← RISK INCREASED
SR-p53      ████░░░░░░  0.60 → 0.58  ≈ unchanged

STATUS: TRADE-OFF — This swap reduces hormonal toxicity but 
        raises mitochondrial risk. A medicinal chemist must decide 
        which pathway matters more for this compound's context.
```

