## Flaw 5 — Explicit Scope Declaration (No Efficacy Model)

### The Error
Replacing a toxic functional group may destroy the therapeutic binding interaction. The pipeline has no efficacy model — it could generate inactive, safe garbage.

### The Correction: Honest Scope Declaration in Code + UI

This is not fixed with code — it is fixed with **explicit framing in the problem statement and UI.**

```python
SCOPE_DISCLAIMER = """
⚠️  SCOPE LIMITATION — READ BEFORE USE

This pipeline optimizes for Tox21-measured in-vitro toxicity ONLY.
It has NO knowledge of:
  - Binding affinity or pharmacological activity
  - In-vivo pharmacokinetics or ADME properties  
  - Target selectivity

A compound modified by this pipeline to be "less toxic" may simultaneously
lose all therapeutic activity. This tool is designed for:
  ✅ Early-stage hit filtering and scaffold prioritization
  ✅ Academic toxicity research and education
  ✅ Environmental/industrial chemical screening

It is NOT designed for:
  ❌ Late-stage lead optimization (use docking + this tool together)
  ❌ Clinical candidate selection
  ❌ Replacement for wet-lab toxicity assays

For leads with known activity, always run a binding affinity model 
(AutoDock Vina, Schrödinger Glide, or similar) AFTER this pipeline.
"""
```

**Why this makes the project stronger:** Honest scoping is a mark of scientific maturity. A professor is more impressed by a student who knows their tool's limits than one who oversells.

